\description{
The Bayesian flagship of cpaic. The relative effect of every treatment is
the sum of its component effects, estimated jointly from individual patient
data (IPD) and aggregate data (AgD). Aggregate arms are fitted by
integrating the individual-level model over each study's covariate
distribution, averaging the outcome on its natural scale (not the link
scale). Because disconnected sub-networks share component parameters, the
network is connected by construction.
}
\details{
The model includes component x effect-modifier interactions \code{gamma}, so the
treatment effect is \strong{population-specific}:
\deqn{\theta_t(x) = C_t' (\beta + \Gamma x).}
The component main effects \code{beta} are the effects at the covariate origin
(\code{x = 0}) and are \emph{not} by themselves a population-adjusted quantity. Use
\code{newdata} in \code{\link[=relative_effects]{relative_effects()}} / \code{\link[=component_effects]{component_effects()}} to obtain effects
in a named target population.

Supported families: \code{"binomial"} (logit), \code{"gaussian"} (identity),
\code{"poisson"} (log), and \code{"survival"}.
}
\section{Integration}{

Aggregate covariates are integrated with Sobol' quasi-Monte-Carlo points
coupled by a Gaussian copula, whose correlation is pooled \emph{within} IPD
studies on the Fisher z scale (or supplied via \code{cor}). Each covariate is
pushed through its own marginal inverse CDF: \code{margins} may be \code{"normal"}
(using \code{x_mean} and \code{x_sd}) or \code{"bernoulli"} (using \code{x_mean} as the
prevalence). Margins default to Bernoulli for covariates that are 0/1 in the
IPD and normal otherwise; a normal margin on a binary covariate would
integrate over a population that cannot occur.
}

\section{Random effects}{

\code{trt_effects = "random"} adds study-arm deviations around the
component-implied relative effects. Deviations use a non-centered
parameterization by default. Within a multi-arm study, deviations relative
to the study baseline have the standard NMA correlation of 0.5. The
heterogeneity standard deviation \code{tau} has a half-normal(0, 1) prior by
default. The centered parameterization is available only to reproduce
sampling comparisons.
}

\section{Priors}{

Defaults follow the Stan prior-choice recommendations. Component effects
use normal(0, 2.5), component by effect-modifier interactions use
normal(0, 1), study intercepts use normal(0, 2.5), and \code{tau} uses
half-normal(0, 1). Interaction priors do real regularization when Gamma is
weakly identified, so every fitted object records the complete prior
specification. Use \code{\link[=prior_sensitivity]{prior_sensitivity()}} to quantify contrast movement and
\code{prior_predictive = TRUE} with \code{\link[=prior_predictive_check]{prior_predictive_check()}} to inspect prior
implications before fitting the likelihood.
}

\section{Survival}{

Survival uses the exact individual likelihood ported from \code{multinma}
(Phillippo et al. 2020). The model evaluates a hazard basis and its
integrated cumulative-hazard basis at every outcome, interval start, and
delayed-entry time. It supports observed events, right censoring, left
censoring, interval censoring, and delayed entry. \code{baseline = "piecewise"}
gives a piecewise-exponential baseline; \code{baseline = "mspline"} gives a
continuous cubic M-spline baseline.

Aggregate survival input must contain reconstructed event and censoring rows
with the same outcome-time columns as IPD, plus repeated arm-level covariate
summaries. The likelihood of every aggregate row is averaged over its
covariate integration points with \code{log_sum_exp}. Aggregate event counts and
person-time alone cannot recover this likelihood and are rejected explicitly.

Two qualifications, so that "exact" is not read more broadly than it should
be.
\itemize{
\item \strong{The likelihood is exact; the covariate integration is not.} Every
individual contribution (event, right, left and interval censoring, delayed
entry) is the exact analytic expression, verified against closed form to
machine precision. The \emph{aggregate} likelihood, however, averages that exact
contribution over a finite quasi-Monte-Carlo grid of \code{n_int} covariate
points, so it carries an integration error that shrinks with \code{n_int} but is
not zero. Increase \code{n_int} and confirm that the estimates are stable before
relying on them. The earlier person-time approximation was biased by 36\% in
a two-group example; that particular bias is removed, but a finite
integration error remains.
\item \strong{The baseline hazard SHAPE is shared across studies.} Each study has its
own baseline level through its intercept, but a single set of spline (or
step) coefficients is shared, so the studies are assumed to have
proportional baseline hazards. \code{multinma} permits study-specific baseline
shapes. If the studies plausibly have differently shaped baselines, this
model is misspecified and the shared shape should not be used.
}
}

\section{Identifiability}{

A relative effect is uniquely estimable only if its component contrast lies
in the row space of the within-study component design (Wigle et al. 2026);
\code{\link[=relative_effects]{relative_effects()}} returns \code{NA} otherwise rather than a prior-driven
number. Note this checks identification of \code{beta}; a component x
effect-modifier interaction is additionally identified only by covariate
variation on the contrasts that involve it, and interactions informed only
by aggregate arms are weakly identified (\code{prior_gamma_scale} regularizes).
}

